00:03:18.980 --> 00:03:22.300
So for starters, what part of
Buddhism am I talking about?

00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:24.800
I'm talking about what you might
call the naturalistic part.

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:29.480
I'm not getting into like, you
know, reincarnation and so on.

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:32.540
Talking about the parts that
are amenable to examination

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:34.710
via modern psychology,
modern philosophy.

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:37.580
And that's the kind of
examination I do in the book.

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:42.970
If you ask, what in particular
am I saying is true?

00:03:42.970 --> 00:03:44.600
There's a number
of answers to that.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:48.950
But one thing I'd say is
at the core of Buddhism

00:03:48.950 --> 00:03:51.830
is the claim that
the reason we suffer

00:03:51.830 --> 00:03:53.840
and the reason we make
other people suffer

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:56.580
is because we don't
see the world clearly.

00:03:56.580 --> 00:03:57.080
OK.

00:03:57.080 --> 00:03:58.930
We don't see ourselves clearly.

00:03:58.930 --> 00:04:00.890
We don't see other
people clearly.

00:04:00.890 --> 00:04:03.530
As a result, we
suffer needlessly,

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:09.405
and we behave badly
towards other people.

00:04:09.405 --> 00:04:11.780
When you think about it, that's
kind of an amazing claim.

00:04:11.780 --> 00:04:12.280
Right?

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:13.340
The idea.

00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:17.930
Because it suggested that
by clarifying your vision,

00:04:17.930 --> 00:04:20.779
by pursuing truth, you
could make yourself happier

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:22.250
and make yourself
a better person.

00:04:22.250 --> 00:04:26.780
So that the idea is that truth
and goodness and happiness

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:28.532
can, in principle, converge.

00:04:28.532 --> 00:04:29.990
So you can kind of
kill three birds

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:32.090
with one stone you might say.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:35.660
Which is nice, you
know, convenient.

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:37.910
And, of course, Buddhism
provides the stone.

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:43.040
It provides a whole set
of teachings and practice

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.910
that are intended to
clarify your vision

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:50.390
and have these very welcome
consequences of that.

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:53.540
The practice
includes meditation,

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:55.320
and I focus a lot
on that in the book.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.220
I talk about mindfulness
meditation in particular.

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:04.440
I'm sure all of you either
do it or have heard of it.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.009
It needs no
introduction these days.

00:05:07.009 --> 00:05:09.300
I think a lot of people think
of mindfulness meditation

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:11.100
as basically therapeutic.

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:12.990
They think of it as
for stress reduction

00:05:12.990 --> 00:05:14.070
or dealing with anxiety.

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:15.850
And it can do those things.

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:18.570
But I think what's lost
is that there really

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:21.180
is a connection between
mindfulness meditation

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:23.220
and the depths of
Buddhist philosophy,

00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:25.984
really deep issues in
Buddhist philosophy.

00:05:25.984 --> 00:05:28.275
And I think people who are
doing mindfulness meditation

00:05:28.275 --> 00:05:29.970
in a kind of therapeutic
way are closer

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:32.160
than they realize
to really serious

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.760
philosophical and
spiritual exploration.

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:37.680
And in the book I
try to provide some

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:42.944
of the background that will
help them make that connection.

00:05:42.944 --> 00:05:44.610
Now, obviously, I'm
not the first person

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:45.820
to say that Buddhism is true.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:46.890
Many people have said it.

00:05:46.890 --> 00:05:51.450
Buddhists, for example, have
been saying it for 2,500 years.

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:53.002
Obviously the
premise of this title

00:05:53.002 --> 00:05:54.960
is that I have something
new to say about that.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:57.000
And you might ask,
who am I to claim

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.820
that I have something new to
say about a subject that's

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:03.870
been so discussed for so long?

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:05.850
The good news is I
don't claim that I

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.100
had some special meditative
revelation that I'm

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:10.210
going to share with you.

00:06:10.210 --> 00:06:12.420
In fact, one difference
between this book

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:14.850
and a lot of books that get
into Buddhist meditation

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:17.490
is this book is not
by someone who is

00:06:17.490 --> 00:06:18.900
especially good at meditating.

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:21.930
Many of them are by people who
are very good at meditating.

00:06:21.930 --> 00:06:23.760
Meditation didn't
come naturally to me.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:30.240
I finally had to go to a retreat
to see enough benefits for me

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:31.530
to really make it a practice.

00:06:34.759 --> 00:06:36.050
I've done a number of retreats.

00:06:36.050 --> 00:06:38.480
And on retreat, in particular,
I have had some experiences

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:41.780
that seem kind of deep.

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:46.130
But I'm not one of these adepts
who have these experiences

00:06:46.130 --> 00:06:48.410
on a more regular basis,
or even in a sense

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:53.810
walk around in daily life
with the benefit of radically

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:55.571
different apprehensions
of the world.

00:06:55.571 --> 00:06:57.320
But I did interview a
lot of these people,

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:00.330
and so their voices
are heard in the book.

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:08.760
And so I hope that helps my
exposition of my argument.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:11.067
But still, I did not come
down from a mountaintop

00:07:11.067 --> 00:07:12.650
with any kind of
special illumination,

00:07:12.650 --> 00:07:14.150
you will be happy to hear.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:18.230
What I'm arguing is that there
is a kind of illumination

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:22.250
of the logic behind Buddhist
philosophy and psychology that

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:24.840
is available now that
just wasn't available 40,

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:26.090
50 years ago.

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:27.650
And it's modern
psychology, and in

00:07:27.650 --> 00:07:30.680
particular, evolutionary
psychology, which

00:07:30.680 --> 00:07:35.150
is the study of how
natural selection designed,

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:38.519
so to speak, in quotes,
"designed" the human mind.

00:07:38.519 --> 00:07:40.560
Now, I wrote a book about
evolutionary psychology

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:44.040
a long time ago called,
"The Moral Animal".

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:47.402
And one thing I realized
when I wrote that--

00:07:47.402 --> 00:07:49.860
well, I realized a couple of
things that in retrospect have

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:52.080
real connections to Buddhism,
and I emphasized them

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:54.070
in the book.

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:56.400
One is that people are
not designed to be happy.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:57.840
OK.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:00.660
Natural selection, that's not
high on natural selection's

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:01.220
agenda.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:03.284
The bottom line for
natural selection

00:08:03.284 --> 00:08:04.950
is getting genes in
the next generation.

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:07.410
Traits that get genes
into the next generation

00:08:07.410 --> 00:08:09.110
are the traits that flourish.

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:12.060
Whether they make you
happy, sad, or whatever.

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:14.460
And that seems to explain
why, as some of you

00:08:14.460 --> 00:08:17.550
probably noticed, gratification
tends to evaporate.

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:18.660
Right?

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:20.010
You eat some food.

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:21.350
You have some sex, whatever.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:23.850
Before long the
thrill fades and you

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:25.200
wouldn't mind having some more.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:26.150
Right?

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:29.434
Now, that makes sense
from the point of view

00:08:29.434 --> 00:08:30.600
of natural selection, right?

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:33.734
Because if you imagine animals
that were eternally contented.

00:08:33.734 --> 00:08:35.400
If they ate one meal
and just sat there,

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.299
and boy that was great.

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:38.007
And didn't seek any
more food, well, they

00:08:38.007 --> 00:08:39.809
wouldn't do well, right?

00:08:39.809 --> 00:08:41.642
And so too with sex.

00:08:41.642 --> 00:08:44.100
From natural selection's point
of view, more sex is better,

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:46.050
more chances to
reproduce are better.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:49.140
So you wouldn't want someone
to just bask in the afterglow

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:54.860
forever after a
single sexual episode.

00:08:54.860 --> 00:08:58.386
So this is consistent
with one thing

00:08:58.386 --> 00:08:59.760
that the Buddha
emphasized, which

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.180
is that there is a lot of
suffering in life as ordinarily

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:02.680
lived.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:04.950
And in fact, this
very phenomenon

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:09.570
is emphasized in Buddhism,
the fleetingness of pleasure.

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:13.740
And in fact, the word that
is translated as suffering--

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:14.926
duka--

00:09:14.926 --> 00:09:18.900
a lot of people think that
a good translation of that

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:20.970
might be unsatisfactoriness.

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:23.280
And that certainly
meshes very well

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.020
with a kind of
evolutionary perspective.

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:28.920
It's unsatisfactoriness that you
would expect natural selection

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:31.620
to build into us, to want us
to always want a little more,

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:34.130
to be discontented.

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:41.170
Now, I said that Buddhism
emphasizes our failure

00:09:41.170 --> 00:09:42.460
to see things clearly.

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:44.260
And you've kind
of seen that here

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:47.110
in the fleetingness of pleasure.

00:09:47.110 --> 00:09:49.540
Because when we look
forward to pleasure,

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:51.340
we tend to look
forward to the pleasure

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:54.610
and not focus on the fact
that it will evaporate, right?

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:56.530
It's kind of an
unbalanced view--

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:58.869
that if you're thinking
about eating some junk food,

00:09:58.869 --> 00:10:00.910
you're thinking about the
taste of the junk food.

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:03.280
Not that, you know,
maybe half an hour later

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:05.200
you'll be restless.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:07.510
If there's some promotion
you've been gunning for,

00:10:07.510 --> 00:10:12.520
you're focusing on the benefits
it'll bring, not the headaches.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:13.660
That's just natural.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:17.200
And you can say that
that's, if not an illusion,

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:22.860
a departure from perfect
balance of vision.

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:27.722
Now, you might say, well, that's
not quite a misperception.

00:10:27.722 --> 00:10:29.180
It's just an
unbalanced perception.

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:29.846
And that's true.

00:10:29.846 --> 00:10:32.230
And you might also say,
look, by and large, people

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:34.300
do a very good job of
perceiving things clearly.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:36.220
They don't run into walls.

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:39.730
They have very good
navigational equipment.

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:40.310
That's true.

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:42.880
But even in that realm,
that simple pedestrian realm

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:45.760
of just perceiving
objects, you do see a kind

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:46.900
of illusion built into it.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:50.930
So people tend to overestimate
the speed at which

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:53.050
large objects approach.

00:10:53.050 --> 00:10:55.150
Now you can see why
that would make sense.

00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:56.500
There's no way of knowing
for sure that that's

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.980
built by natural selection, but
it surely makes sense, right?

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:00.479
Because it's better
safe than sorry.

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:02.560
Better to get out of
the way of a big animal

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:04.870
or whatever too
soon than too late.

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:09.340
And I say that just to make the
point that strictly speaking

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:12.430
just as our happiness is not
high on natural selection's

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:17.700
agenda, strictly speaking
accuracy of perception is not.

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:20.620
If inaccuracy in perception,
if illusion will get genes

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:22.570
into the next
generation, then that

00:11:22.570 --> 00:11:27.270
can be favored by
natural selection.

00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:32.777
And in this realm of
better safe than sorry--

00:11:32.777 --> 00:11:34.610
the principle that leads
you to overestimate

00:11:34.610 --> 00:11:36.240
the speed of an object--

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:42.920
you kind of see how these two
things, illusion and suffering,

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:44.480
can again coincide.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.510
So if you were like walking
through, taking a hike,

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:49.760
and you've heard that there
are rattlesnakes all over.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:51.834
Every time you hear
a rustling, you're

00:11:51.834 --> 00:11:54.000
going to kind of imagine
that there's a snake there.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.709
If a lizard darts
across, you're probably

00:11:55.709 --> 00:11:57.374
going to think it's
a snake for a while.

00:11:57.374 --> 00:11:58.196
That's an illusion.

00:11:58.196 --> 00:11:59.070
It's also unpleasant.

00:11:59.070 --> 00:12:00.250
It's suffering.

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:02.630
But from natural
selection's point of view,

00:12:02.630 --> 00:12:04.889
and maybe even from yours,
all those false positives

00:12:04.889 --> 00:12:05.430
are worth it.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:09.500
But the point is, again,
suffering, illusion,

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:13.920
they can make sense from natural
selection's point of view.

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:18.520
And then, on top of that,
living in an environment

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:20.320
that natural selection
did not prepare us

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:22.930
for compounds things.

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:26.720
So you take forms of suffering
that are in a sense natural,

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:31.420
like anxiety, and they morph
into a whole new difficult

00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:32.720
to manage forms.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.740
So, for example,
evolutionary psychologists

00:12:35.740 --> 00:12:38.140
would say that having
anxiety about a toddler

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:40.450
is natural if it's your
toddler and they wander off.

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:42.491
You'll go, wait, something
horrible has happened.

00:12:42.491 --> 00:12:43.930
Run after them.

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:46.840
But natural selection
didn't equip us for, say,

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:48.304
dropping a toddler
off at a daycare

00:12:48.304 --> 00:12:50.470
center on the first day
where you don't know anybody

00:12:50.470 --> 00:12:51.280
at the daycare center.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.340
And so that's going to just
totally freak people out.

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:53.840
Right?

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:59.050
Or similarly it's natural to
have anxiety about how you're

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:01.510
perceived, because winning
the esteem of people

00:13:01.510 --> 00:13:04.930
seems to have helped get
genes into the next generation

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:06.670
during human evolution.

00:13:06.670 --> 00:13:08.150
But then in the
modern environment,

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:09.790
you put people in
situations like this.

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:12.940
They're addressing a bunch
of people they've never met.

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:16.220
And naturally people have
public speaking anxieties,

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:17.470
and they imagine crazy things.

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:20.050
There are people
who are recurringly

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:21.750
imagined that they
will projectile vomit

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:24.910
while public speaking even
though they've never done it.

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:27.250
And they believe it when
they're having the fear.

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:31.500
And so you've got two problems.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:33.700
We were built to sometimes
suffer and not see things

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:34.390
clearly.

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:37.180
The modern environment in
some ways makes things worse.

00:13:37.180 --> 00:13:42.060
It makes us imagine things
that aren't going to happen,

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:45.200
or are very unlikely
to happen, and so on.

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:51.130
So I fear that in talking
about anxiety and stress

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:54.160
I'm again making meditation
sound like a purely

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:56.260
therapeutic thing.

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:58.890
And I want to
emphasize that I do

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:00.640
think there is a lot
more to it than that.

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:03.505
In the book, I
focus a lot on two

00:14:03.505 --> 00:14:07.520
of the deepest and pretty
central concepts in Buddhism,

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:08.020
I would say.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:09.730
One is called not self.

00:14:09.730 --> 00:14:12.124
The idea that the self is
in some sense an illusion.

00:14:12.124 --> 00:14:13.540
And the other is
called emptiness,

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:15.650
which has a number
of interpretations.

00:14:15.650 --> 00:14:19.390
But it's sometimes
put as the things

00:14:19.390 --> 00:14:22.420
you see do not have
inherent existence,

00:14:22.420 --> 00:14:26.660
or they don't have essences,
or something like that.

00:14:26.660 --> 00:14:28.990
And so both things sound
pretty arcane if you hear them

00:14:28.990 --> 00:14:30.400
for the first time.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:33.970
And I'm not going have time
to get into them deeply here.

00:14:33.970 --> 00:14:35.860
I would say,
though, just quickly

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:38.680
about not self-- a point I try
to emphasize in the book is

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:40.990
that when you do
something that is fairly

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:43.840
common in mindfulness
meditation, which is just

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:46.340
get a different vantage
point on your feelings,

00:14:46.340 --> 00:14:47.759
such as the one
I just described.

00:14:47.759 --> 00:14:49.800
Or even less dramatic than
what I just described.

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:53.410
But just suddenly you
have a little perspective

00:14:53.410 --> 00:14:55.840
on a feeling that previously
you might have been barely

00:14:55.840 --> 00:14:57.756
aware of, but you would
have kind of slavishly

00:14:57.756 --> 00:14:59.050
actually obeyed, right?

00:14:59.050 --> 00:15:01.050
And you get enough
perspective on the feelings

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:02.824
so that they're no
longer in charge.

00:15:02.824 --> 00:15:04.990
And you may even exercise
some choice in whether you

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:06.400
follow their guidance.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:09.790
Well, I would say that when
you do something like that,

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:14.050
you are making an incremental
step toward not self,

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:15.670
toward the experience
of not self.

00:15:15.670 --> 00:15:20.480
And I look at the Buddha's own
early teachings on the subject.

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:23.440
And I think you can interpret
them very much in that spirit--

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:27.170
the kind of so-called first
discourse on not self.

00:15:30.190 --> 00:15:38.130
Now, as for emptiness,
let me just close on that.

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:39.630
We'll talk about
emptiness, and then

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.840
get back to this question
of contemporary politics,

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:46.260
and then open it
up for Q&amp;A. So I

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:49.080
had an experience on my very
first meditation retreat.

00:15:49.080 --> 00:15:51.510
I talked about this in the book.

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:55.140
But I was taking a
walk through the woods,

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:58.350
and I saw a particular weed
called a plantain weed.

00:15:58.350 --> 00:16:00.510
And it was a kind of
weed that had infested

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:03.540
my lawn for years and years.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:05.730
And I had spent a lot of
time trying to pull it up,

00:16:05.730 --> 00:16:07.380
trying to kill it.

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:10.320
And all of a sudden I just
couldn't understand why.

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.260
I looked at the
weed, and I thought,

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:15.570
this weed is just as beautiful
as all the other stuff

00:16:15.570 --> 00:16:17.220
that we're not calling weeds.

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:21.420
There are no objective criterion
for distinguishing weeds

00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:21.920
from not.

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.900
It's just some person
at some point decided

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:28.390
to call certain things
weeds, and so we all do.

00:16:28.390 --> 00:16:31.050
But the feeling at that time
was that it didn't make sense.

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:34.740
And it wasn't just a logical
conclusion I reached.

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.950
It was a perceptual shift.

00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:40.590
When we look at things
we consider weeds,

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:43.380
we sense a kind of
essence of weed.

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.000
And it's a subtle
thing, but it's

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.770
very much informed by feeling.

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:49.470
I would say it's
not just cognitive.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:51.240
It's not just perceptual.

00:16:51.240 --> 00:16:52.980
It's very much
infused by feeling.

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:55.020
And by the way, I would
say one thing in general

00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:59.640
that I think Buddhist psychology
has been very prescient in is

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:03.390
the emphasis on the way feelings
subtly infiltrate what we think

00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:06.030
of as cognition, and
shape our thoughts,

00:17:06.030 --> 00:17:10.041
and attach themselves to
our thoughts, and so on.

00:17:10.041 --> 00:17:11.999
But in any event, I didn't
see essence of weed,

00:17:11.999 --> 00:17:14.880
and suddenly it was beautiful.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:16.859
All the greenery was beautiful.

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:18.780
And by the way, if
you talk to people

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:21.750
who seem to walk around with
the so-called experience

00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:23.579
of emptiness, they
say the same thing.

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:26.460
They say things project
their identities

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:28.780
less sharply than they used to.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:30.517
That just seems
like a little less--

00:17:30.517 --> 00:17:32.350
they know it's a clock
if they look at that.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:35.850
And it's got less clock
vibe than it used to.

00:17:35.850 --> 00:17:38.010
But they also say
everything is beautiful,

00:17:38.010 --> 00:17:41.050
or they may say everything has
a positive energy or something.

00:17:41.050 --> 00:17:44.910
So this brings us back
to contemporary politics,

00:17:44.910 --> 00:17:48.260
in particular the
psychology of tribalism,

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:51.560
which I think is the big
problem with the world.

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:53.510
Wherever the conflict is--

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:57.500
sectarian conflict, ideological
polarization in America,

00:17:57.500 --> 00:17:59.570
national conflict,
wherever you see conflict--

00:17:59.570 --> 00:18:01.670
I think the problem
is what I call

00:18:01.670 --> 00:18:04.820
the psychology of tribalism,
a somewhat misleading term.

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:09.020
But in any event, I would
say a set of cognitive biases

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:12.860
that lead us to--

00:18:12.860 --> 00:18:14.900
well, involve identifying
with one group

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:18.690
and affect the way you
process information

00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:22.260
relevant to your relations
with the other group.

00:18:22.260 --> 00:18:25.400
And I think one good thing
about mindfulness meditation

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:33.560
is it makes you more aware of
how you're feelings trigger

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:34.400
certain biases.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:37.330
So a good example is
the so-called fake news.

00:18:37.330 --> 00:18:37.830
Right?

00:18:37.830 --> 00:18:40.170
And now I personally
think almost all of us

00:18:40.170 --> 00:18:41.720
have spread fake news.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:42.350
I know I have.

00:18:42.350 --> 00:18:44.510
There have been times
when I retweeted something

00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:47.480
without going back and
examining the original source.

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:51.150
And I later realized
it had been misleading.

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:54.080
And if you ask what is it that
leads somebody to do that,

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:55.070
it's a feeling.

00:18:55.070 --> 00:18:58.190
It feels good to
spread information

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:02.320
that is unflattering to
the group you don't like,

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:05.050
or flattering to the group you
like, or confirms the argument

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:06.700
you've already made.

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:08.450
This is sometimes
called confirmation

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:12.730
by evidence consistent
with your preexisting view.

00:19:12.730 --> 00:19:15.290
I just want to emphasize it's
not just a cognitive bias.

00:19:15.290 --> 00:19:17.020
There is a feeling
associated with it.

00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:18.490
I think mindfulness
meditation can

00:19:18.490 --> 00:19:22.210
make you more aware that
that's happening and leads you

00:19:22.210 --> 00:19:26.300
to kind of pause and reflect
before sharing the fake news.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:29.440
Now, to get back to the
essence thing and emptiness.

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:31.050
I think the most
consequential arena

00:19:31.050 --> 00:19:38.470
for emptiness and for not seeing
essence of is the human realm.

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:39.550
Because we do.

00:19:39.550 --> 00:19:42.190
And again, I think this is a
product of natural selection.

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:45.520
We do tend to see essence
of rival, essence of enemy,

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:47.920
essence of friend,
essence of ally.

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:50.680
And these perceptions
shape the way

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:52.600
we process information
about them.

00:19:52.600 --> 00:19:54.529
And there's one
particular cognitive bias

00:19:54.529 --> 00:19:57.070
that hasn't been discussed as
much as I think it needs to be.

00:19:57.070 --> 00:19:59.380
And I want to just
mention that quickly.

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:01.416
So this is called
attribution error.

00:20:01.416 --> 00:20:03.040
The original version
of this was called

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:06.010
the fundamental
attribution error.

00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:09.640
And the idea originally is,
as it was originally studied,

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:13.150
was when we try to explain
somebody's behavior--

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:15.970
why they did something--
we attribute too much

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:17.500
significance to
the kind of person

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:19.870
they are, kind of
essence, you might say,

00:20:19.870 --> 00:20:21.320
and not enough to circumstance.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:23.860
So if somebody in front of
you in the checkout line

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:27.530
is a jerk, is rude to the clerk,
you go, well, that's a jerk.

00:20:27.530 --> 00:20:31.750
That's essence of
jerk, but for all you

00:20:31.750 --> 00:20:33.760
know they just had a bad night.

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:36.160
I was actually a
little rude last night.

00:20:36.160 --> 00:20:40.010
My flight from New Jersey
was eight hours late.

00:20:40.010 --> 00:20:42.580
And so I was just
not in the mood

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:46.900
to find that they did not
have any rental cars for me.

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:49.930
And I kept it fairly
well under control.

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:54.070
But I like to think
that wasn't the real me.

00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:57.100
Anyway, psychologists
have found that--

00:20:57.100 --> 00:20:59.700
they originally found that
there was this bias toward--

00:20:59.700 --> 00:21:01.450
you might say essence--
attributing things

00:21:01.450 --> 00:21:05.015
to a person's disposition
rather than to situation.

00:21:05.015 --> 00:21:07.390
But then they found that it's
actually subtler than that.

00:21:07.390 --> 00:21:09.390
And this is the
interesting part.

00:21:09.390 --> 00:21:12.860
With our friends and allies,
if they do something good,

00:21:12.860 --> 00:21:14.970
we attribute that to
their disposition,

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:17.012
to the kind of person they
are, to their essence.

00:21:17.012 --> 00:21:18.469
That's the kind of
person they are.

00:21:18.469 --> 00:21:19.330
They do good things.

00:21:19.330 --> 00:21:22.470
If they do something bad, we
have a situational explanation.

00:21:22.470 --> 00:21:24.780
They didn't get enough
sleep, like me last night.

00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:26.680
Or they were under stress.

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:29.310
They just got horrible news
about their family, whatever.

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:32.790
With our enemies and
rivals, it's the opposite.

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:35.160
If they do something
bad, it confirms our view

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:36.612
of what their essence is.

00:21:36.612 --> 00:21:38.070
That's the kind of
person they are.

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:40.082
If they do something
good, we explain it away.

00:21:40.082 --> 00:21:41.790
They just succumb to
peer group pressure.

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:43.680
They're showing off or whatever.

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:46.350
This is hugely consequential.

00:21:46.350 --> 00:21:49.620
You may have noticed that
when we're ramping up

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:52.470
for war, people who favor the
invasion go to great lengths

00:21:52.470 --> 00:21:54.900
to paint the leader
of the country

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:58.377
we might invade as
demonically as possible.

00:21:58.377 --> 00:22:00.210
Sometimes these people
don't need much help.

00:22:00.210 --> 00:22:01.418
Sometimes they're bad people.

00:22:01.418 --> 00:22:04.270
But the point is that
if you favor invasion,

00:22:04.270 --> 00:22:07.230
it makes sense to put
them in that enemy's box.

00:22:07.230 --> 00:22:10.390
Because once they're there,
it's very hard to get out.

00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:12.480
But anything good they do
will be explained away.

00:22:12.480 --> 00:22:15.240
Anything bad they do will
confirm the initial image.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:19.130
And I think the same thing
plays out in our politics.

00:22:19.130 --> 00:22:27.570
So I think just a great
contribution mindfulness

00:22:27.570 --> 00:22:30.690
meditation can make
here is to make

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:33.810
us more aware of the feelings
that trigger various cognitive

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:34.380
biases.

00:22:34.380 --> 00:22:37.110
That get us to retweet things
or share them on Facebook

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:38.150
without checking them.

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:41.370
That get us to think
unfairly unflattering things

00:22:41.370 --> 00:22:44.160
about people.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:47.790
And to get back to
natural selection--

00:22:47.790 --> 00:22:49.800
I think to become
aware of your feelings

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:51.900
and decide whether or
not to do their bidding

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:55.580
is almost to launch
a kind of rebellion

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:56.940
against natural selection.

00:22:56.940 --> 00:23:00.920
Because feelings are
just the key levers that

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:03.680
are used to kind of
get us to follow what

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:05.677
you might call natural
selection's agenda.

00:23:05.677 --> 00:23:07.760
And parts of natural
selection's agenda are great.

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:14.630
It built a lot of things into
us that I'm grateful for--

00:23:14.630 --> 00:23:17.660
love, gratitude itself,
speaking of being grateful.

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:20.690
There's a lot of nice things.

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:24.492
But I think we have
the power to look up

00:23:24.492 --> 00:23:26.450
at the process that built
us, decide whether we

00:23:26.450 --> 00:23:27.575
want to follow as dictates.

00:23:27.575 --> 00:23:30.686
And I think meditation
can be a big help here.

00:23:30.686 --> 00:23:34.150
I just want to quickly
say two things,

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:38.000
and one is just a
bit of promotion.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:42.701
I started a site called
mindfulresistance.net.

00:23:42.701 --> 00:23:44.630
I only started it
a few weeks ago.

00:23:44.630 --> 00:23:48.674
Right now we're just putting
out a weekly newsletter.

00:23:48.674 --> 00:23:50.090
Of course, the
term resistance has

00:23:50.090 --> 00:23:52.160
become associated with
resistance against Trump,

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:54.920
and I have to admit
I'm not a fan of Trump.

00:23:54.920 --> 00:23:57.950
But I mean resistance a little
more broadly and deeply.

00:23:57.950 --> 00:24:02.810
I mean fighting the forces that
gave rise to the mess we're in,

00:24:02.810 --> 00:24:05.060
which certainly includes
the psychology of tribalism

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:08.640
and also includes a lot of
social political things.

00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:10.730
Figuring out how to
respond to challenges

00:24:10.730 --> 00:24:14.060
posed by globalization,
technology, and so on.

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:18.440
But my own feeling is that
a lot of opponents of Trump

00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:22.220
overreact to him in ways that
actually play into his hands.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:23.370
That's kind of an aside.

00:24:23.370 --> 00:24:25.490
But in general, I
think that whatever

00:24:25.490 --> 00:24:27.440
fight you're fighting,
fighting it mindfully

00:24:27.440 --> 00:24:29.030
is just good strategy.

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:35.020
And not getting too sucked
into reacting to things.

00:24:35.020 --> 00:24:38.890
So that's mindfulresistance.net.

00:24:38.890 --> 00:24:42.620
Final thing, and I should
admit before I say this,

00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:44.120
I am prone to
apocalyptic thinking,

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:47.240
so you should discount
this accordingly.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:50.070
But I think you
could make the case

00:24:50.070 --> 00:24:52.350
that we are at a
point in history

00:24:52.350 --> 00:24:56.550
where the only alternative to
much deeper chaos and strife

00:24:56.550 --> 00:25:01.170
is for people to become more
aware of how their minds work

00:25:01.170 --> 00:25:04.230
and seize some control,
some conscious control

00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:05.790
of that process.

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:08.190
Meditation isn't the
only way to do that.

00:25:08.190 --> 00:25:10.740
Now, in my experience,
it's the most effective.

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:14.220
But there are various ways
to become, including just

00:25:14.220 --> 00:25:15.740
reading about cognitive biases.

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:17.250
There are a lot
of ways to get out

00:25:17.250 --> 00:25:19.380
what you might
call metacognition,

00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:20.850
but I think we
may need something

00:25:20.850 --> 00:25:25.700
like a metacognitive revolution
if the planet is going

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:27.680
to do what it is poised to do.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.820
Which is, kind of
cross the threshold

00:25:30.820 --> 00:25:33.970
to form a cohesive
global community.

00:25:33.970 --> 00:25:36.850
As opposed to just collapsing
back into chaos, which I think

00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:39.190
is a real possibility
given some of the forces

00:25:39.190 --> 00:25:41.440
I see at work and some of
the positive feedback loops

00:25:41.440 --> 00:25:43.360
that are at work.

00:25:45.900 --> 00:25:51.180
But I think one
way or other people

00:25:51.180 --> 00:25:56.370
need very much to get clear on
how their minds are distorting

00:25:56.370 --> 00:25:58.920
their perception of
reality and warping

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:02.490
their judgment of others and
their treatment of others.

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:06.090
And if, as Buddhism
suggests, that makes them

00:26:06.090 --> 00:26:08.070
not just better people
but happier people,

00:26:08.070 --> 00:26:09.700
well, that's a nice bonus.

00:26:09.700 --> 00:26:10.986
Thank you.

00:26:10.986 --> 00:26:13.974
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:22.930
SPEAKER 2: So we have time for
