00:26:27.550 --> 00:26:29.020
AUDIENCE: I have
a question here.

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:31.660
So you just mentioned the
political situation here

00:26:31.660 --> 00:26:34.480
in the US.

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:36.610
It sounds like a
lot of people are

00:26:36.610 --> 00:26:41.740
having a lot of illusions
over the other side,

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.080
probably that's causing
a lot of conflicts.

00:26:44.080 --> 00:26:47.800
I wonder if there's a way for
them to calm down and really

00:26:47.800 --> 00:26:51.822
have a meaningful discussion
instead of fighting each other?

00:26:51.822 --> 00:26:53.027
Thank you.

00:26:53.027 --> 00:26:53.860
ROBERT WRIGHT: Yeah.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:59.620
That reminds me of another
thing that I consider

00:26:59.620 --> 00:27:03.490
a cognitive bias that
doesn't get discussed much

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:07.090
in these terms, and it's this--

00:27:07.090 --> 00:27:09.850
and I think this may be built
in by natural selection, built

00:27:09.850 --> 00:27:11.440
into the mind, but
that's conjecture.

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:15.150
But you may have
noticed that if you

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.900
try to explain why someone
who did something bad

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:22.620
did the thing, somebody will
immediately say, oh, so you're

00:27:22.620 --> 00:27:24.102
saying it's not their fault?

00:27:24.102 --> 00:27:25.560
You're saying
they're not to blame?

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:31.100
Well, to take a--

00:27:31.100 --> 00:27:32.570
no, I won't get into that.

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:34.640
The recent example is
too highly charged.

00:27:34.640 --> 00:27:38.081
But if you try to explain,
like, why do people join ISIS?

00:27:38.081 --> 00:27:40.580
It's like, oh, you're saying
the terrorists aren't to blame?

00:27:40.580 --> 00:27:41.300
You know?

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:45.980
And this is an example of
an impediment to what you're

00:27:45.980 --> 00:27:53.250
talking about, which is
sitting down and just

00:27:53.250 --> 00:27:56.880
trying to understand
if you're anti-Trump,

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:00.570
why people voted for Trump.

00:28:00.570 --> 00:28:04.800
I have three siblings who voted
for Trump out of four siblings.

00:28:04.800 --> 00:28:08.850
So it's three to
two if you count me.

00:28:08.850 --> 00:28:11.420
And it's hard.

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:15.630
[LAUGHS] I'm so angry,
but this is the big--

00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:17.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:21.720
-- this is the biggest
challenge we face.

00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:23.400
And I'll do another plug.

00:28:23.400 --> 00:28:25.290
I have a platform
called bloggingheads.tv

00:28:25.290 --> 00:28:29.840
where we try to do a better
job than many platforms do

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.239
of hearing the other side.

00:28:32.239 --> 00:28:33.780
I've had a number
of Trump supporters

00:28:33.780 --> 00:28:36.910
on and talked to them.

00:28:36.910 --> 00:28:38.680
But it's hard.

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:42.385
And that's why I say I have
some hope that just mindfulness

00:28:42.385 --> 00:28:45.010
and meditation, if it
continues to spread,

00:28:45.010 --> 00:28:46.630
will play a positive role.

00:28:46.630 --> 00:28:49.075
And I want to
emphasize one thing.

00:28:49.075 --> 00:28:50.700
One thing people say
is, wait a second,

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:54.730
if our side meditates and we are
calm, they'll just run us over,

00:28:54.730 --> 00:28:56.200
right?

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:58.270
No, I think
unilateral disarmament

00:28:58.270 --> 00:28:59.451
in this context works.

00:28:59.451 --> 00:28:59.950
OK?

00:28:59.950 --> 00:29:02.210
Because I think-- to
get back to Trump--

00:29:02.210 --> 00:29:05.810
I think a lot of times
when people aren't calm

00:29:05.810 --> 00:29:08.650
and reacting to him,
that's what he wants.

00:29:08.650 --> 00:29:10.540
That's playing into
his hands, because it's

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:13.870
feeding his narrative
that everyone hates him.

00:29:13.870 --> 00:29:16.810
That narrative
appeals to his base.

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:20.479
And that's just one example
of how, in general, I think

00:29:20.479 --> 00:29:21.770
with these kinds of conflicts--

00:29:21.770 --> 00:29:25.000
Now, obviously, if
it's an armed conflict,

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.190
and you literally surrender your
weapons and they come kill you,

00:29:28.190 --> 00:29:30.550
that is not good strategy.

00:29:30.550 --> 00:29:32.980
But I think in this realm
we're talking about,

00:29:32.980 --> 00:29:36.020
just deep political
polarization,

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:41.380
I think that progress on
one side, on either side,

00:29:41.380 --> 00:29:44.320
can set in motion
forces that will

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:48.400
lead to a kind of calming
effect on the other side.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:51.730
And it can be a virtuous cycle.

00:29:51.730 --> 00:29:56.148
But this is a huge challenge.

00:29:56.148 --> 00:29:58.710
SPEAKER 2: So to ask questions,
please line up back here.

00:29:58.710 --> 00:30:00.830
I guess it works out
better for the AV

00:30:00.830 --> 00:30:02.650
if we just line up and ask.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:04.230
Thank you.

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:06.960
AUDIENCE: So you
started to touch on this

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:10.150
with the political resistance.

00:30:10.150 --> 00:30:14.490
So if someone who's skilled in
meditation has a tooth ache,

00:30:14.490 --> 00:30:17.160
maybe they can
contemplate the pain

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:19.740
and behold it and
view it with distance.

00:30:19.740 --> 00:30:23.070
But at what point should
they just go to the dentist?

00:30:23.070 --> 00:30:30.590
And where does the desire for
contentment with your situation

00:30:30.590 --> 00:30:35.700
end, and when you should start
to think about making a change?

00:30:35.700 --> 00:30:37.490
Like, why don't we just--

00:30:37.490 --> 00:30:42.600
could we just sit passively
and tolerate the administration

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:45.722
because we're very
good at dissociating?

00:30:45.722 --> 00:30:47.180
ROBERT WRIGHT: The
tooth ache thing

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:48.971
I actually did, and I
describe in the book.

00:30:48.971 --> 00:30:51.650
I was on a retreat, and I
developed an abscessed tooth.

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:55.350
And when I drank any liquid,
it was excruciatingly painful.

00:30:55.350 --> 00:30:58.039
So I meditated for half an
hour, just as an experiment,

00:30:58.039 --> 00:30:59.080
and then had a lot of it.

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:00.347
And it was a surprising thing.

00:31:00.347 --> 00:31:02.180
I don't mean it took
all the pain out of it,

00:31:02.180 --> 00:31:05.030
but it kind of vacillated
between acute pain

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:07.400
and just going, whoa, that's
an amazing wave of pain.

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:08.900
And when I did that,
it didn't hurt.

00:31:08.900 --> 00:31:11.580
It was really surprising, but
I know that's not the question.

00:31:11.580 --> 00:31:15.099
The question is
with actual teeth.

00:31:15.099 --> 00:31:16.890
The answer is you should
go to the dentist.

00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:20.850
But I think the main context
for your question is--

00:31:23.721 --> 00:31:26.220
well, you hear this a lot, tell
me if this is what you mean.

00:31:26.220 --> 00:31:33.390
Will meditation kind of end
my passion for social justice,

00:31:33.390 --> 00:31:37.440
or for change, or for resistance
against forces of oppression?

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:40.770
And to be honest,
I have seen people

00:31:40.770 --> 00:31:42.870
who had gone so
far down the path

00:31:42.870 --> 00:31:45.280
that I think that had happened.

00:31:45.280 --> 00:31:47.320
I think it's very rare.

00:31:47.320 --> 00:31:52.620
I think for people
like me, you care

00:31:52.620 --> 00:31:56.130
enough about certain
issues that the challenge

00:31:56.130 --> 00:32:00.390
is to pursue them wisely
and not get caught up

00:32:00.390 --> 00:32:03.330
in your hatred of the people
on the other side and so on.

00:32:03.330 --> 00:32:07.710
So it's like a larger
philosophical question

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:09.510
associated with
Buddhism, of nihilism,

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:10.920
which I won't get into.

00:32:10.920 --> 00:32:14.070
But it's an interesting
"in principle" question.

00:32:14.070 --> 00:32:17.430
In my experience, in practice
it doesn't arise very often.

00:32:17.430 --> 00:32:20.730
But anyway, I would say
if you get that far,

00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:27.420
if you're so good at insulating
yourself from the world--

00:32:27.420 --> 00:32:30.840
which in a certain sense is part
of what meditation is about,

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:32.680
learning to get
better at coping.

00:32:32.680 --> 00:32:35.170
If you get so good
that you don't care,

00:32:35.170 --> 00:32:37.610
then I would say you've gone
farther than I want to go.

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:38.610
It doesn't happen often.

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:44.060
AUDIENCE: Well,
it's not a question.

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:46.820
Could you talk about
more about the projects

00:32:46.820 --> 00:32:48.030
you are working on right now?

00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:51.870
How they can really
help the society?

00:32:51.870 --> 00:32:52.370
Thanks.

00:32:52.370 --> 00:32:54.203
ROBERT WRIGHT: The
mindful resistance thing?

00:32:54.203 --> 00:32:56.110
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
and if you can talk

00:32:56.110 --> 00:32:58.210
about several other things.

00:32:58.210 --> 00:33:00.660
The one that you are feeling
most interesting about

00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:02.720
or meaningful about.

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:03.910
ROBERT WRIGHT: Yeah, OK.

00:33:03.910 --> 00:33:07.420
Well, the mindful
resistance, like I

00:33:07.420 --> 00:33:10.816
said, we started
it a few weeks ago.

00:33:10.816 --> 00:33:13.090
The URL is
mindfulresistance.net.

00:33:13.090 --> 00:33:17.360
All we're doing right now is
putting out a weekly newsletter

00:33:17.360 --> 00:33:20.210
kind of summarizing events.

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:21.680
And we're still
finding our voice

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:24.380
but trying to do it
in a different way

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:29.510
than people in the
resistance per se do it.

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:37.990
And both not get caught up in
reacting to every provocation,

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:42.250
and also trying to
convey what's going

00:33:42.250 --> 00:33:45.014
on in the minds
of the other side,

00:33:45.014 --> 00:33:46.180
of people who support Trump.

00:33:46.180 --> 00:33:48.490
Because a lot of time
that doesn't come through.

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:56.149
Because most people who oppose
Trump don't watch Fox News.

00:33:56.149 --> 00:33:57.940
But I think it's
illuminating to know that.

00:33:57.940 --> 00:34:03.850
Now, honestly, this is, I
hope, just the primordial stage

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:04.750
of this project.

00:34:04.750 --> 00:34:07.360
And that eventually
we will actually

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:10.630
try to get people
mobilized to try

00:34:10.630 --> 00:34:13.000
to become more productive
citizens in the way

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:14.080
I've described.

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:19.060
You know, try to actually make
a point of not sharing news

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:20.920
without checking it out.

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:26.520
And not needlessly
ridiculing people

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:30.690
unless you're pretty sure
it's going to be productive.

00:34:30.690 --> 00:34:34.090
There have been times in history
where ridicule was important.

00:34:34.090 --> 00:34:38.850
But I would like to
develop an actual program

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:44.100
for applying mindfulness, in
the everyday English sense,

00:34:44.100 --> 00:34:47.010
to participation in
politics, in public life,

00:34:47.010 --> 00:34:48.150
by just regular citizens.

00:34:48.150 --> 00:34:50.250
Because I think that's
where it has to go.

00:34:50.250 --> 00:34:57.310
If you ask, well, why do various
opinion leaders, people on CNN,

00:34:57.310 --> 00:35:00.810
Fox News, MSNBC, why do
they seem so incendiary

00:35:00.810 --> 00:35:01.980
in the way they talk?

00:35:01.980 --> 00:35:04.170
Because they get positive
reinforcement for it.

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:05.100
They get viewers.

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:06.780
They get retweets.

00:35:06.780 --> 00:35:09.585
Ultimately, in that sense,
the people are in charge.

00:35:09.585 --> 00:35:11.460
It's just that it takes
a whole bunch of them

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:12.790
to make a difference.

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:22.290
In other words, I don't
want to confine this

00:35:22.290 --> 00:35:25.290
to people who meditate.

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:29.010
At the same time, I think
meditation can be very helpful.

00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:31.500
And I do want to emphasize
to people who don't meditate

00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:34.350
that mindfulness meditation--

00:35:34.350 --> 00:35:36.630
if you look at the term,
and the origin of the term,

00:35:36.630 --> 00:35:38.130
and the choice of
the word "mindful"

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:40.830
to translate to Buddhist term
"sati" and all of this stuff--

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.740
they may think of mindfulness as
just like, whoa, stop and smell

00:35:46.740 --> 00:35:48.480
the roses.

00:35:48.480 --> 00:35:50.130
Or just getting
absorbed in yourself

00:35:50.130 --> 00:35:52.830
and like, oh, my feelings.

00:35:52.830 --> 00:35:58.275
But ultimately, mindfulness is
about real clarity of vision.

00:36:02.410 --> 00:36:04.680
The person who chose mindfulness
to translate the term

00:36:04.680 --> 00:36:08.280
"sati", a British civil
servant and scholar

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:10.560
who went over to, I
think, Burma and got

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.870
engrossed in the culture.

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:15.140
He said that the Buddhist
ideal of so-called right

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:16.890
mindfulness-- and this
is one of the eight

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:18.710
factors in the Eightfold
Path in Buddhism--

00:36:18.710 --> 00:36:22.040
is sati, mindfulness, what's
been translated as mindfulness.

00:36:22.040 --> 00:36:26.490
He said it's like a
clear, alert mind.

00:36:26.490 --> 00:36:27.660
That is mindfulness.

00:36:27.660 --> 00:36:33.780
Not unswayed by emotional
reaction, just clear and alert.

00:36:33.780 --> 00:36:38.110
And I think that would
be real progress.

00:36:38.110 --> 00:36:42.290
AUDIENCE: You talked a lot
about mindfulness as potential

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:44.690
to overcome cognitive biases.

00:36:44.690 --> 00:36:47.120
And there seems to be
a lot of literature

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:50.060
about the problems
with cognitive biases,

00:36:50.060 --> 00:36:52.160
and that they do,
in fact, exist.

00:36:52.160 --> 00:36:54.200
In the book, do you
go over evidence

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:56.900
that mindfulness
can in fact overcome

00:36:56.900 --> 00:36:57.890
these cognitive biases?

00:36:57.890 --> 00:37:01.040
I'm aware of mindfulness
reducing anxiety and increasing

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:02.870
compassion, but
in terms of seeing

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:04.700
more clearly biases, is there--

00:37:04.700 --> 00:37:07.906
ROBERT WRIGHT: I'm not aware
of studies that have been done.

00:37:07.906 --> 00:37:10.280
I know I gave a talk before
the book came out at Rutgers,

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:16.100
and a couple of people
there made the suggestion

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:18.260
that they should
start working on that

00:37:18.260 --> 00:37:20.120
and actually study
whether mind-- it's

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:23.210
a fairly straightforward
thing to study.

00:37:23.210 --> 00:37:25.850
You have a control group and
another group that meditates,

00:37:25.850 --> 00:37:27.680
and you give them
cognitive bias tests

00:37:27.680 --> 00:37:29.660
at the beginning and the end.

00:37:29.660 --> 00:37:31.670
And so I don't know
what's become of that.

00:37:31.670 --> 00:37:34.380
I'm not aware of--

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:37.580
in fact, I'm not
that aware of a lot

00:37:37.580 --> 00:37:40.730
of work on the role of
feelings and emotions

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:42.320
in triggering cognitive biases.

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:45.880
But I feel very strongly,
just intuitively

00:37:45.880 --> 00:37:48.600
and based on meditative
introspection,

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:50.710
that that's really fundamental.

00:37:50.710 --> 00:37:54.360
That it's all about feelings,
in terms of triggering them.

00:37:57.846 --> 00:38:02.070
AUDIENCE: So how do you deal
with the conflicting experience

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:05.712
with really attributing an
error to somebody's character

00:38:05.712 --> 00:38:07.420
just because you don't
know them clearly?

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:11.400
Where the natural instinct
of considering the worst case

00:38:11.400 --> 00:38:15.090
scenario, where there might be
something that's really wrong,

00:38:15.090 --> 00:38:17.490
or it might be just
because you're not

00:38:17.490 --> 00:38:19.490
able to see it really clearly.

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:22.740
And you don't know what
exactly the person is

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:23.785
or what exactly the--

00:38:23.785 --> 00:38:26.640
ROBERT WRIGHT: So you
mean how in everyday life

00:38:26.640 --> 00:38:29.317
should you go about trying to
figure out what the issue is?

00:38:29.317 --> 00:38:31.400
AUDIENCE: In general,
especially in a lot of cases

00:38:31.400 --> 00:38:33.330
when we deal with
a lot of people

00:38:33.330 --> 00:38:35.790
we may not know exactly
what the thing is.

00:38:35.790 --> 00:38:38.510
But one of the primitive
natural instincts

00:38:38.510 --> 00:38:40.920
is when something
doesn't appear right,

00:38:40.920 --> 00:38:44.880
we tend to think negatively
and attribute negative aspects

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:47.420
to people or
situations or groups.

00:38:47.420 --> 00:38:52.180
So how exactly is
suggestible to deal with it?

00:38:52.180 --> 00:38:58.950
ROBERT WRIGHT: Yeah, I
think I would advocate

00:38:58.950 --> 00:39:00.740
a stance of firm agnosticism.

00:39:00.740 --> 00:39:03.920
In other words, sometimes
you just don't know.

00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:06.560
Until you know more
about the situation,

00:39:06.560 --> 00:39:08.330
you just don't know
whether they regularly

00:39:08.330 --> 00:39:11.150
behave like this in
all circumstances,

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:12.950
or they just had a bad day.

00:39:12.950 --> 00:39:16.160
So you reserve judgment.

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:21.900
And this issue of
judgment is like--

00:39:21.900 --> 00:39:24.070
you hear it a lot in the
context of mindfulness.

00:39:24.070 --> 00:39:26.320
It's like, don't make
judgments, don't make judgments.

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:31.180
And sometimes people
dismiss that like, what?

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:32.259
You don't have values?

00:39:32.259 --> 00:39:33.550
You don't make moral judgments?

00:39:33.550 --> 00:39:36.500
And it's not that.

00:39:36.500 --> 00:39:39.610
It's just don't make judgments
about stuff you don't know.

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:43.150
And that's very hard.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:45.430
And I get into this
in the book about how

00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:48.760
our brains seem designed to
make really quick judgments.

00:39:53.620 --> 00:39:58.057
If a quick judgment is
right 51% of the time,

00:39:58.057 --> 00:39:59.890
then from natural
selection's point of view,

00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:01.723
in certain circumstances,
it might be better

00:40:01.723 --> 00:40:02.950
than agnosticism, right?

00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:10.840
But that's not a good
reason for reaching quick--

00:40:10.840 --> 00:40:12.366
AUDIENCE: In a lot
of situations it

00:40:12.366 --> 00:40:18.230
might be required for you to
be able to evaluate or come

00:40:18.230 --> 00:40:20.033
to a decision than
just keeping it

00:40:20.033 --> 00:40:22.250
as an abstract way
of understanding

00:40:22.250 --> 00:40:23.459
and just dragging it forever.

00:40:23.459 --> 00:40:25.916
ROBERT WRIGHT: Well, do you
have a specific kind of example

00:40:25.916 --> 00:40:27.610
in mind, where you
might have to--

00:40:27.610 --> 00:40:32.660
AUDIENCE: For example, my
point that I'm coming from

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:35.820
is-- there could be a lot of
people with inherent biases

00:40:35.820 --> 00:40:36.320
as well.

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:39.730
But then they actually have
those biases because they

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:43.042
actually believe in them.

00:40:43.042 --> 00:40:44.750
Whether intentionally
or unintentionally,

00:40:44.750 --> 00:40:46.275
somehow the brains
get programmed

00:40:46.275 --> 00:40:50.390
because of the past
experiences or whatever.

00:40:50.390 --> 00:40:53.360
But then they may not be
able to really see the facts

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:56.382
but still need to
make decisions.

00:40:56.382 --> 00:40:59.480
Let's say whether they want to
continue working with somebody

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:03.544
or not, or whether they want
to really stay with someone

00:41:03.544 --> 00:41:05.346
or not.

00:41:05.346 --> 00:41:07.220
Even like hiring
someone or not, things

00:41:07.220 --> 00:41:08.960
like that, where
you can't really

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:10.707
indefinitely delay things.

00:41:10.707 --> 00:41:12.290
ROBERT WRIGHT: Yeah,
so you're talking

00:41:12.290 --> 00:41:16.100
about like group stereotypes
and biases, like ethnic bias,

00:41:16.100 --> 00:41:18.030
and so on?

00:41:18.030 --> 00:41:21.090
I think that some of the
social science literature

00:41:21.090 --> 00:41:23.370
shows that what's
most constructive

00:41:23.370 --> 00:41:26.250
is if you find yourself in
a non-zero sum situation

00:41:26.250 --> 00:41:27.890
with somebody in that group.

00:41:27.890 --> 00:41:31.080
In other words, you can
benefit by, in some sense,

00:41:31.080 --> 00:41:34.470
doing business with them,
or it's in your interest

00:41:34.470 --> 00:41:37.350
to collaborate with them.

00:41:37.350 --> 00:41:39.570
I'm guessing-- I don't
fly business class--

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:43.146
but I'm guessing you don't see
a lot of expressions of bigotry.

00:41:43.146 --> 00:41:44.520
Because for one
thing, you've got

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:46.353
these different ethnic
groups doing business

00:41:46.353 --> 00:41:47.460
with one another, right?

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:52.470
It pays to be polite in
a situation like that.

00:41:52.470 --> 00:41:54.600
There's a lot of
evidence of that.

00:41:54.600 --> 00:41:59.300
And I think homosexuality
is an interesting case.

00:41:59.300 --> 00:42:02.270
Because if you ask why
values changed so fast

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:06.110
toward acceptance
of homosexuality,

00:42:06.110 --> 00:42:08.630
that was an interesting
case where a lot of people

00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:09.890
knew gay people.

00:42:09.890 --> 00:42:11.720
They just didn't
know they were gay.

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:14.990
And once gay people started
coming out of the closet,

00:42:14.990 --> 00:42:16.650
then more people
started coming out,

00:42:16.650 --> 00:42:18.108
and more people
started coming out,

00:42:18.108 --> 00:42:20.670
and pretty soon everyone
had a cousin or a friend.

00:42:20.670 --> 00:42:25.070
And so when you're in that kind
of relationship with someone,

00:42:25.070 --> 00:42:27.470
you're just more
inclined to be tolerant.

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:30.320
And the challenge
is when there aren't

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:32.180
enough of those kinds
of relationships

00:42:32.180 --> 00:42:35.420
between two groups.

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:38.210
And once it's torn apart,
it's hard to reassemble.

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:39.830
You know, Sunni and
Shia in Iraq used

00:42:39.830 --> 00:42:43.790
to get together a lot better
than they did before the war,

00:42:43.790 --> 00:42:45.260
before we invaded.

00:42:45.260 --> 00:42:48.068
And so I don't know.

00:42:48.068 --> 00:42:48.900
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:53.430
So I'm asking this question on
behalf of a group of Googlers.

00:42:53.430 --> 00:42:57.280
We had this email
thread about this topic.

00:42:57.280 --> 00:43:00.480
So recently there has
been a lot of effort

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:01.975
into secularizing
Buddhism, right?

00:43:01.975 --> 00:43:02.850
ROBERT WRIGHT: Right.

00:43:02.850 --> 00:43:05.940
AUDIENCE: So there is a
lot of focus on meditation

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:08.130
and mindfulness, but
then we leave out

00:43:08.130 --> 00:43:11.430
the core aspects of Buddhism,
like reincarnation and cause

00:43:11.430 --> 00:43:12.780
and effect.

00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:15.082
So in Buddhism, there
are two concepts

00:43:15.082 --> 00:43:16.290
to explain everything, right?

00:43:16.290 --> 00:43:19.530
Like the relative truth
and the ultimate truth.

00:43:19.530 --> 00:43:21.870
As a Buddhist myself,
in ultimate truth,

00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:23.490
I don't believe
in reincarnation.

00:43:23.490 --> 00:43:25.270
I don't believe in
cause and effect.

00:43:25.270 --> 00:43:26.760
There is no self, right?

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:30.180
But in relative truth, for me,
not believing in reincarnation

00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:32.580
is like I don't believe in time.

00:43:32.580 --> 00:43:37.650
So if you consider
yourself Buddhist,

00:43:37.650 --> 00:43:41.970
why not explain things
in those two concepts,

00:43:41.970 --> 00:43:44.520
like in the relative truth
and in the ultimate truth?

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:45.420
ROBERT WRIGHT: So
by cause and effect,

00:43:45.420 --> 00:43:47.460
you probably mean what's
commonly called karma, right?

00:43:47.460 --> 00:43:47.815
AUDIENCE: Correct.

00:43:47.815 --> 00:43:48.510
ROBERT WRIGHT: Right.

00:43:48.510 --> 00:43:50.210
AUDIENCE: These topics
are considered esoteric--

00:43:50.210 --> 00:43:51.570
ROBERT WRIGHT: I say that
because, just quickly,

00:43:51.570 --> 00:43:53.550
one thing that's not
appreciated by Buddhism

00:43:53.550 --> 00:43:55.200
is that karma aside.

00:43:55.200 --> 00:43:57.420
It really puts a lot of
emphasis on cause and effect

00:43:57.420 --> 00:44:00.180
in the scientific
side, in a sense,

00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:02.130
at least as much as
Western science does.

00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:06.480
If you really look at
what is meant by-- well,

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.520
the rationales for both
not self and emptiness

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:12.480
turn out to involve a really
pervasive appreciation

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:14.520
of the pervasiveness
of causal influence.

00:44:14.520 --> 00:44:21.664
But that aside, first of all--

00:44:21.664 --> 00:44:22.830
and I say this in the book--

00:44:22.830 --> 00:44:25.050
I actually don't
call myself Buddhist.

00:44:25.050 --> 00:44:28.500
Because I am doing
mindfulness meditation,

00:44:28.500 --> 00:44:31.710
I'm doing it in the explicit
context of Buddhist philosophy.

00:44:31.710 --> 00:44:35.160
And in the book, I defend
some of the fundamental ideas,

00:44:35.160 --> 00:44:37.050
not self emptiness and so on.

00:44:37.050 --> 00:44:41.330
But I just worry
that to Buddhists

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:44.619
who are Buddhist in a
religious sense, it might--

00:44:44.619 --> 00:44:45.160
I don't know.

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:48.016
It might seem disrespectful
or something for me to show up

00:44:48.016 --> 00:44:49.890
and say, well, you know,
I buy the philosophy

00:44:49.890 --> 00:44:50.580
and the psychology.

00:44:50.580 --> 00:44:52.204
So I'm going to call
myself a Buddhist.

00:44:52.204 --> 00:44:52.860
I don't know.

00:44:52.860 --> 00:44:54.318
I feel a little
awkward about that.

00:44:54.318 --> 00:44:57.266
I think it's fine for people
who are doing so-called Western

00:44:57.266 --> 00:44:59.640
Buddhism or secular Buddhism
to call themselves Buddhist.

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:04.510
I actually don't,
because I don't

00:45:04.510 --> 00:45:08.830
get into karma, reincarnation,
and so on at all.

00:45:08.830 --> 00:45:13.010
It's not part of my
practice or my belief.

00:45:13.010 --> 00:45:14.220
Is that at all responsive?

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:15.620
AUDIENCE: Yeah, yeah.

00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:18.440
I have read that
some Buddhists--

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:22.130
hardcore Buddhists-- they say
that the dilution of Buddhism,

00:45:22.130 --> 00:45:24.050
what's happening in
the West, is actually

00:45:24.050 --> 00:45:27.820
a big threat to this
2,500 tradition.

00:45:27.820 --> 00:45:28.605
Right?

00:45:28.605 --> 00:45:31.890
ROBERT WRIGHT: Yeah.

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:33.534
In my experience,
my previous book

00:45:33.534 --> 00:45:34.950
was called "The
Evolution of God."

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:36.491
It was about the
Abrahamic religions.

00:45:36.491 --> 00:45:41.970
And one thing you notice is
just spiritual traditions evolve

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:43.397
forever, and they branch off.

00:45:43.397 --> 00:45:45.980
Look at how many different kinds
of Buddhism there are, right?

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:50.307
And there are some non-trivial
differences of doctrine within.

00:45:50.307 --> 00:45:52.890
That's one problem some people
have with why Buddhism is true.

00:45:52.890 --> 00:45:54.480
There's no one Buddhism.

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:57.240
And that's why I focused
on pretty core concepts

00:45:57.240 --> 00:46:00.010
like not self.

00:46:00.010 --> 00:46:05.020
So that's one thing you can
say is that in a certain sense,

00:46:05.020 --> 00:46:06.580
every version of
every religion is

00:46:06.580 --> 00:46:09.880
threatened by its own future
evolution in a certain sense.

00:46:18.895 --> 00:46:21.270
Just quickly-- one thing that's
characteristic of Western

00:46:21.270 --> 00:46:23.220
Buddhism is meditation.

00:46:23.220 --> 00:46:24.720
Westerners think
that Buddhists are

00:46:24.720 --> 00:46:28.050
people who meditate and
don't believe in God.

00:46:28.050 --> 00:46:30.110
Well, in Asia, that's the
opposite of the truth.

00:46:30.110 --> 00:46:33.579
They do believe not in a single
creator God but in deities.

00:46:33.579 --> 00:46:35.120
And they don't
meditate by and large.

00:46:35.120 --> 00:46:37.010
Laypeople don't
meditate in Asia.

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:38.834
But actually, the tradition--

00:46:38.834 --> 00:46:41.000
AUDIENCE: That's the laypeople
you're talking about.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:42.500
ROBERT WRIGHT: The
laypeople, right.

00:46:42.500 --> 00:46:45.350
But what I was going to say
was even there, in Burma,

00:46:45.350 --> 00:46:48.050
in the late 19th
century, in reaction

00:46:48.050 --> 00:46:52.670
to colonial occupation, they did
establish a big lay meditation

00:46:52.670 --> 00:46:54.110
tradition.

00:46:54.110 --> 00:46:57.510
And a lot of Western--

00:46:57.510 --> 00:46:59.840
kind of Theravada,
Vipassana Buddhism--

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:01.860
traces its lineage to that.

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:03.830
So in a certain
sense, this feature

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:05.270
of so-called
Western Buddhism has

00:47:05.270 --> 00:47:08.990
roots in Asian Buddhism
as it evolved in response

00:47:08.990 --> 00:47:14.710
to forces 100, 140 years ago.

00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:20.830
So on the one hand, I
definitely respect the view

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:25.080
that Western Buddhists should
not call themselves Buddhists,

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:27.480
and that's why I
don't call myself one.

00:47:27.480 --> 00:47:29.310
But at the same time--

00:47:29.310 --> 00:47:31.890
well, I guess I certainly--

00:47:31.890 --> 00:47:38.090
another way to look
at it is, isn't there

00:47:38.090 --> 00:47:40.340
something valuable about
what's happening in the West?

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:49.540
A. And B, I think it's richer if
informed by Buddhist philosophy

00:47:49.540 --> 00:47:51.070
than if not.

00:47:51.070 --> 00:47:54.280
And in a way this gets
into the whole issue

00:47:54.280 --> 00:47:56.620
of cultural
appropriation and so on,

00:47:56.620 --> 00:47:58.570
which is above my pay grade.

00:48:01.490 --> 00:48:03.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:03.640 --> 00:48:08.020
AUDIENCE: You have a question
on the mindfulness meditation

00:48:08.020 --> 00:48:12.110
potential, in terms of
introducing that early in life.

00:48:12.110 --> 00:48:15.970
I think many of us have accessed
some of these tools later

00:48:15.970 --> 00:48:17.380
in life than we
would have hoped.

00:48:17.380 --> 00:48:19.330
And it seems like there's
a lot of potential

00:48:19.330 --> 00:48:23.140
to offset some of the
negative aspects that

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:25.300
are just fundamental
to our nature in terms

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:34.135
of the tribalism and the biases
that we absorb over time.

00:48:34.135 --> 00:48:35.760
What are your thoughts
on the potential

00:48:35.760 --> 00:48:38.605
to introduce these tools
maybe earlier in life?

00:48:38.605 --> 00:48:40.350
ROBERT WRIGHT: Oh,
I'm all for it.

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:41.130
AUDIENCE: And are you
seeing any trends?

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:42.380
ROBERT WRIGHT: I'm all for it.

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:47.010
And this gets to the question
of Buddhism as a label.

00:48:47.010 --> 00:48:49.890
Because if you
talk to people who

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:52.110
are trying to introduce
mindfulness meditation

00:48:52.110 --> 00:48:55.149
in the public schools,
a lot of them will say

00:48:55.149 --> 00:48:57.690
it's a lot easier if they don't
use the word "Buddhism," just

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:58.606
as a political matter.

00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:02.730
We have one
congressman so far as I

00:49:02.730 --> 00:49:05.280
know who is into mindfulness
meditation, Tim Ryan,

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:09.450
and he has found in talking to
his constituents and so on he

00:49:09.450 --> 00:49:14.605
needs to emphasize that
this is not at odds--

00:49:14.605 --> 00:49:16.230
the part of Buddhism
he's talking about

00:49:16.230 --> 00:49:20.940
is not at odds with any
existing religious heritage

00:49:20.940 --> 00:49:22.980
these people may have.

00:49:22.980 --> 00:49:24.817
And I think he's by
and large not using

00:49:24.817 --> 00:49:25.900
the term "Buddhism" a lot.

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:27.180
The people who are--

00:49:27.180 --> 00:49:30.410
there's like a "Mindful
Magazine" or something.

00:49:30.410 --> 00:49:32.760
I think something mindful.

00:49:32.760 --> 00:49:36.480
And they don't want to talk
about Buddhism, because they're

00:49:36.480 --> 00:49:38.910
introducing meditation into
institutional settings,

00:49:38.910 --> 00:49:41.430
corporate settings, and so on.

00:49:41.430 --> 00:49:44.820
So to some extent, that
divorce from the label

00:49:44.820 --> 00:49:47.130
is going to happen
as part of the quest

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:51.740
to more deeply ingrain our
society with meditation.

00:49:51.740 --> 00:49:55.514
And maybe it's a worthwhile
trade, I don't know,

00:49:55.514 --> 00:49:57.680
but I'm certainly in favor
of starting people young.

00:50:01.400 --> 00:50:03.100
AUDIENCE: So our
modern environment

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:05.290
has produced conditions
in everyday life that

00:50:05.290 --> 00:50:08.625
are not conducive to
sustained focus and attention.

00:50:08.625 --> 00:50:10.000
What are some of
the consequences

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.700
of our fractured
attention spans?

00:50:12.700 --> 00:50:14.785
And does current science
provide any insight?

00:50:14.785 --> 00:50:17.782
ROBERT WRIGHT: You're
asking the right person.

00:50:17.782 --> 00:50:19.240
I've always had
attention problems.

00:50:22.570 --> 00:50:24.220
I never emerge from
a college lecture

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:25.920
with a coherent set of notes.

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:26.650
And I tried.

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:27.500
I really did.

00:50:27.500 --> 00:50:30.650
I just couldn't do it.

00:50:30.650 --> 00:50:35.910
And one thing-- I get into
this a little in the book.

00:50:35.910 --> 00:50:39.880
The point is just that,
again, as is often the case,

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:44.320
attention problems
are largely I think

00:50:44.320 --> 00:50:46.120
problems of affect, of feeling.

00:50:46.120 --> 00:50:47.680
If you pay attention--

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:49.870
like if I'm trying
to do some writing,

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:52.990
and I suddenly switch over
and check my Twitter feed,

00:50:52.990 --> 00:50:56.052
or get back to researching some
smartphone I'm going to buy.

00:50:56.052 --> 00:50:57.760
If you look at what's
actually happening,

00:50:57.760 --> 00:50:59.800
first, I've reached a
point in the writing

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:01.630
where it's not coming
easily, and that

00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:03.700
makes me feel uneasy
and uncomfortable.

00:51:03.700 --> 00:51:05.320
That's a bad feeling.

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:07.729
Something pops in my mind
like researching smart phones,

00:51:07.729 --> 00:51:08.770
checking my Twitter feed.

00:51:08.770 --> 00:51:10.240
It gives me a good feeling.

00:51:10.240 --> 00:51:11.560
And it's that simple.

00:51:11.560 --> 00:51:17.500
Attention is very much an
affective issue, I think.

00:51:17.500 --> 00:51:20.800
Now, the problem's gotten
worse because there

00:51:20.800 --> 00:51:23.909
are so many people
on the internet

00:51:23.909 --> 00:51:25.450
trying to get you
addicted to things.

00:51:30.580 --> 00:51:33.640
The other thing I'd say is I
think one reason meditation

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:36.757
retreats seem to be
growing in appeal

00:51:36.757 --> 00:51:39.340
is because one thing they do--
set aside the meditation-- they

00:51:39.340 --> 00:51:41.037
can just get you off the grid.

00:51:41.037 --> 00:51:43.120
And by the way, if you go
to a meditation retreat,

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:48.910
I strongly recommend you put
your email on auto reply,

00:51:48.910 --> 00:51:51.250
leave your smartphone
at home or whatever.

00:51:51.250 --> 00:51:53.170
Just get totally
absorbed, no news

00:51:53.170 --> 00:51:56.330
from the outside world,
that for my money

00:51:56.330 --> 00:51:59.710
is a way to do a
meditation retreat.

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:04.000
I just think that so amplifies
the beneficial effects

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.690
of the meditation itself.

00:52:06.690 --> 00:52:08.300
And it's a good reminder.

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:10.090
Of course, in the end, you have
to go back to the real world.

00:52:10.090 --> 00:52:12.100
And this is, of course, the
problem of meditation retreats

00:52:12.100 --> 00:52:12.600
in general.

00:52:12.600 --> 00:52:13.110
They end.

00:52:13.110 --> 00:52:15.730
And then it's everything
that came easily

00:52:15.730 --> 00:52:19.650
by the end of the
retreat is harder.

00:52:19.650 --> 00:52:24.100
But it's still a good
reminder of how much--

00:52:24.100 --> 00:52:26.620
if a retreat goes well-- they
usually do in my experience--

00:52:26.620 --> 00:52:29.990
by the end of the retreat, your
state of mind is so different.

00:52:29.990 --> 00:52:34.120
It's just a reminder
of how in everyday life

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:37.420
your mind is just pushed
and pulled increasingly

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:42.980
by electronic things.

00:52:42.980 --> 00:52:44.980
So you're probably young
enough you don't really

00:52:44.980 --> 00:52:46.646
totally remember the
pre-internet world.

00:52:46.646 --> 00:52:55.258
Believe me, it was different

